}
\details{
The .SW0 file defines the initial soil water conditions for each layer at the
start of the AquaCrop simulation. These conditions significantly affect early
crop growth and development.
\subsection{Initial Conditions:}{
\itemize{
\item \strong{Canopy cover}: Set to -9.00 to let AquaCrop calculate, or specify actual value (0-100\%)
\item \strong{Biomass}: Usually 0 at planting, but can specify pre-existing biomass
\item \strong{Root depth}: Set to -9.00 for automatic, or specify initial depth in meters
}
}

\subsection{Soil Textures and Default Wilting Points:}{

The function uses the \code{\link{SWOData}} dataset which contains wilting point values
for 12 standard USDA soil textures. See \code{data(SWOData)} for details.
}

\subsection{Water Content Levels:}{
\itemize{
\item \strong{Wilting Point (WP)}: Minimum water for plant survival (texture-specific)
\item \strong{Field Capacity (FC)}: WP × 1.5 (approximate)
\item \strong{Saturation (SAT)}: WP × 2.5 (approximate)
}
}

\subsection{Salinity Levels:}{

Use \code{\link{salinity_to_ece}} to convert qualitative descriptions to ECe values:
\itemize{
\item "none": 0 dS/m (non-saline)
\item "slight": 3 dS/m (slightly saline)
\item "moderate": 6 dS/m (moderately saline)
\item "strong": 12 dS/m (strongly saline)
\item "very strong": 20 dS/m (very strongly saline)
}
}
}
